</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Coronary artery anomalies constitute a diverse group of abnormalities, ranging from anatomic variants to those having hemodynamic consequences. This review focuses on major anomalies that have clinical implications requiring treatment, including anomalous origin of the coronary artery from the opposite sinus with interarterial course specifically with an intramural course, coronary artery origin from the pulmonary artery, and coronary artery fistula. Comprehensive imaging evaluation is necessary to precisely delineate the anatomy as well as pathophysiologic aspects of the anomaly before determining treatment options for a specific patient. Coronary computed tomographic angiography provides elegant depiction of coronary arterial anatomy and the relationship of the vessel to the adjacent structures, with the ability to perform three-dimensional reconstructions. Magnetic resonance (MR) imaging is emerging as an alternative noninvasive imaging strategy, particularly in young individuals, due to the lack of ionizing radiation and avoidance of iodinated contrast agents. This review describes the roles and recent technical advancements in computed tomography and MR imaging pertinent to coronary artery imaging. Additionally, this article will familiarize readers with the cross-sectional imaging appearance of clinically relevant coronary anomalies, hemodynamic considerations, and complex decision making. The different management strategies used for these anomalies, such as coronary unroofing, reimplantation, bypass grafting, Takeuchi repair, and surgical and interventional closure of fistulas, as well as specific posttreatment complications, are also discussed.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2017</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2017160124">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2017160124">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160124/asset/images/large/rg.2017160124.fig1.jpeg" height="1396" width="1599" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. Diagram shows origin (arrow) of the left main coronary artery from the right aortic sinus <i>(R)</i> with an interarterial course between the aorta and the pulmonary artery <i>(P)</i>. <i>L</i> = left aortic sinus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160124&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160124/asset/images/large/rg.2017160124.fig2.jpeg" height="1326" width="1597" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span>. Diagram shows the intramural segment (arrows) of an interarterial left main coronary artery coursing within the aortic wall. <i>L</i> = left aortic sinus, <i>R</i> = right aortic sinus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160124&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160124/asset/images/large/rg.2017160124.fig3.jpeg" height="1487" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span>. Interarterial left main coronary artery in a 64-year-old man with chest pain and an anomalous coronary artery found at invasive coronary angiography. Coronary CT image obtained to further evaluate course of the anomalous artery demonstrates a common origin of the right coronary artery <i>(RCA)</i> and left main coronary artery (<i>LM</i>) from the right sinus of Valsalva (<i>RSV</i>). The left main coronary artery, surrounded by epicardial fat, courses between the aortic root (<i>Ao</i>) and the pulmonary artery (<i>PA</i>) to reach its distal myocardial territory. There is no narrowing, slitlike ostium, or acute angle takeoff to suggest an intramural segment. <i>LSV</i> = left sinus of Valsalva, <i>NCS</i> = noncoronary sinus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160124&amp;id=fig3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160124/asset/images/large/rg.2017160124.fig4a.jpeg" height="1789" width="1100" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Interarterial left main coronary artery in a 17-year-old boy with chest pain. <b>(a)</b> Curved multiplanar reformatted CT image demonstrates the acute angle takeoff of the left main coronary artery <i>(LM)</i> from the right sinus of Valsalva <i>(RSV)</i>. Note the narrowing (arrow) of the proximal left main coronary artery corresponding to the intramural segment within the aortic wall, which attains a normal caliber distally. <b>(b)</b> Orthogonal cross-sectional image of the narrowed proximal segment shows the classic elliptical cross section (arrow), which is indicative of an intramural course.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160124&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160124/asset/images/large/rg.2017160124.fig4b.jpeg" height="1442" width="1550" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Interarterial left main coronary artery in a 17-year-old boy with chest pain. <b>(a)</b> Curved multiplanar reformatted CT image demonstrates the acute angle takeoff of the left main coronary artery <i>(LM)</i> from the right sinus of Valsalva <i>(RSV)</i>. Note the narrowing (arrow) of the proximal left main coronary artery corresponding to the intramural segment within the aortic wall, which attains a normal caliber distally. <b>(b)</b> Orthogonal cross-sectional image of the narrowed proximal segment shows the classic elliptical cross section (arrow), which is indicative of an intramural course.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160124&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160124/asset/images/large/rg.2017160124.fig5a.jpeg" height="1202" width="1503" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. Diagrams show the technique of coronary unroofing for an interarterial coronary artery with an intramural segment. The intramural course is opened up over its entire length (along the dashed line in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>), thereby creating a wide neo-ostium without angulation or a slitlike opening <b>(c)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160124&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160124/asset/images/large/rg.2017160124.fig5b.jpeg" height="1203" width="1095" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. Diagrams show the technique of coronary unroofing for an interarterial coronary artery with an intramural segment. The intramural course is opened up over its entire length (along the dashed line in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>), thereby creating a wide neo-ostium without angulation or a slitlike opening <b>(c)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160124&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160124/asset/images/large/rg.2017160124.fig5c.jpeg" height="1202" width="1097" aria-labelledby="fig5c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5c</span>. Diagrams show the technique of coronary unroofing for an interarterial coronary artery with an intramural segment. The intramural course is opened up over its entire length (along the dashed line in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>), thereby creating a wide neo-ostium without angulation or a slitlike opening <b>(c)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160124&amp;id=fig5c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160124/asset/images/large/rg.2017160124.fig6a.jpeg" height="1456" width="1297" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. Interarterial left main coronary artery in a 32-year-old man with episodes of exercise-induced syncope. <b>(a)</b> Preoperative axial CT image shows an anomalous interarterial left main artery arising from the right sinus near the left-right commissural post. Note the slitlike ostium and short intramural course (arrow). The intramural course was confirmed at surgery, and the portion of the aortic wall was unroofed. <b>(b)</b> Image after unroofing shows the patent larger caliber left main coronary artery neo-ostium (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160124&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160124/asset/images/large/rg.2017160124.fig6b.jpeg" height="1456" width="1318" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. Interarterial left main coronary artery in a 32-year-old man with episodes of exercise-induced syncope. <b>(a)</b> Preoperative axial CT image shows an anomalous interarterial left main artery arising from the right sinus near the left-right commissural post. Note the slitlike ostium and short intramural course (arrow). The intramural course was confirmed at surgery, and the portion of the aortic wall was unroofed. <b>(b)</b> Image after unroofing shows the patent larger caliber left main coronary artery neo-ostium (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160124&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160124/asset/images/large/rg.2017160124.fig7a.jpeg" height="1040" width="1478" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. Interarterial RCA in a 23-year-old man with a history of cardiac arrest while riding a bike. <b>(a)</b> Preoperative oblique axial CT image shows an interarterial <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr> from the left sinus. <b>(b)</b> The patient underwent reimplantation with a normal postoperative appearance. The proximal RCA was found to be hypoplastic without an intramural course; the hypoplastic segment was removed at surgery. <i>L</i> = left, <i>R</i> = right.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160124&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160124/asset/images/large/rg.2017160124.fig7b.jpeg" height="1040" width="971" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. Interarterial RCA in a 23-year-old man with a history of cardiac arrest while riding a bike. <b>(a)</b> Preoperative oblique axial CT image shows an interarterial <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr> from the left sinus. <b>(b)</b> The patient underwent reimplantation with a normal postoperative appearance. The proximal RCA was found to be hypoplastic without an intramural course; the hypoplastic segment was removed at surgery. <i>L</i> = left, <i>R</i> = right.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160124&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160124/asset/images/large/rg.2017160124.fig8a.jpeg" height="1556" width="1332" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. Intramural interarterial <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr> in a 39-year-old woman after bypass grafting with a right internal mammary artery (<abbr title="right internal mammary artery">RIMA</abbr>) to the <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr>. The <abbr title="right internal mammary artery">RIMA</abbr> subsequently occluded, presumably owing to competitive flow. <b>(a)</b> Volume-rendered CT image shows surgical clips (white arrows) of the occluded <abbr title="right internal mammary artery">RIMA</abbr> landing zone, adjacent to the proximal <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr>. <b>(b)</b> Axial maximum intensity projection CT image shows the intramural <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr> (arrow) coursing between the aortic root <i>(Ao)</i> and the pulmonary artery <i>(PA)</i>. The patient subsequently underwent successful unroofing of the <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160124&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160124/asset/images/large/rg.2017160124.fig8b.jpeg" height="1556" width="1317" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. Intramural interarterial <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr> in a 39-year-old woman after bypass grafting with a right internal mammary artery (<abbr title="right internal mammary artery">RIMA</abbr>) to the <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr>. The <abbr title="right internal mammary artery">RIMA</abbr> subsequently occluded, presumably owing to competitive flow. <b>(a)</b> Volume-rendered CT image shows surgical clips (white arrows) of the occluded <abbr title="right internal mammary artery">RIMA</abbr> landing zone, adjacent to the proximal <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr>. <b>(b)</b> Axial maximum intensity projection CT image shows the intramural <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr> (arrow) coursing between the aortic root <i>(Ao)</i> and the pulmonary artery <i>(PA)</i>. The patient subsequently underwent successful unroofing of the <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160124&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160124/asset/images/large/rg.2017160124.fig9.jpeg" height="1856" width="1399" aria-labelledby="fig9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span>. Diagram shows the coronary circulation after birth in an anomalous <abbr title="left coronary artery">LCA</abbr> arising from the pulmonary artery. Collaterals (<b>*</b>) develop between the left and right coronary systems, and flow in the anomalous coronary artery becomes retrograde into the pulmonary artery <i>(P)</i>. Myocardial steal phenomenon leads to hypoperfusion of the <abbr title="left coronary artery">LCA</abbr> territory (blue area).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160124&amp;id=fig9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160124/asset/images/large/rg.2017160124.fig10a.jpeg" height="1743" width="1404" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. ALCAPA in a 22-year-old man with a history of a syncopal event while playing soccer. Axial contrast-enhanced <b>(a)</b> and curved planar reformatted <b>(b)</b> CT images show the anomalous <abbr title="left coronary artery">LCA</abbr> (<b>*</b>) arising from the pulmonary artery <i>(P)</i>. The markedly dilated <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr> (arrow) arises from the aorta <i>(A)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160124&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160124/asset/images/large/rg.2017160124.fig10b.jpeg" height="1743" width="1046" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. ALCAPA in a 22-year-old man with a history of a syncopal event while playing soccer. Axial contrast-enhanced <b>(a)</b> and curved planar reformatted <b>(b)</b> CT images show the anomalous <abbr title="left coronary artery">LCA</abbr> (<b>*</b>) arising from the pulmonary artery <i>(P)</i>. The markedly dilated <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr> (arrow) arises from the aorta <i>(A)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160124&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160124/asset/images/large/rg.2017160124.fig11.jpeg" height="1798" width="1398" aria-labelledby="fig11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11</span>. Diagram shows a coronary button transfer procedure. The pulmonary trunk <i>(P)</i> is transected and the anomalous coronary artery is removed with a button of tissue. The proximal anomalous coronary artery is mobilized and anastomosed (arrow) to the aortic root <i>(A)</i>. The pulmonary artery is repaired with autologous pericardium (<b>*</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160124&amp;id=fig11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160124/asset/images/large/rg.2017160124.fig12a.jpeg" height="1662" width="1497" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. Diagrams show Takeuchi repair. This involves creation <b>(a)</b> of an aortopulmonary window (arrow). The pulmonary artery <i>(P)</i> is opened and an anterior flap of tissue from it is used <b>(b)</b> to create an intrapulmonary tunnel (<b>*</b>) that baffles the aorta <i>(A)</i> to the anomalous coronary ostium <b>(c)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160124&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160124/asset/images/large/rg.2017160124.fig12b.jpeg" height="1674" width="1465" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. Diagrams show Takeuchi repair. This involves creation <b>(a)</b> of an aortopulmonary window (arrow). The pulmonary artery <i>(P)</i> is opened and an anterior flap of tissue from it is used <b>(b)</b> to create an intrapulmonary tunnel (<b>*</b>) that baffles the aorta <i>(A)</i> to the anomalous coronary ostium <b>(c)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160124&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160124/asset/images/large/rg.2017160124.fig12c.jpeg" height="1674" width="1474" aria-labelledby="fig12c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12c</span>. Diagrams show Takeuchi repair. This involves creation <b>(a)</b> of an aortopulmonary window (arrow). The pulmonary artery <i>(P)</i> is opened and an anterior flap of tissue from it is used <b>(b)</b> to create an intrapulmonary tunnel (<b>*</b>) that baffles the aorta <i>(A)</i> to the anomalous coronary ostium <b>(c)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160124&amp;id=fig12c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160124/asset/images/large/rg.2017160124.fig13a.jpeg" height="1701" width="1028" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. Takeuchi repair in a 36-year-old woman with <abbr title="anomalous origin of the left coronary artery from the pulmonary artery">ALCAPA</abbr>. MR imaging still frame <b>(a)</b> from two-dimensional (<abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr>) <abbr title="steady-state free precession">SSFP</abbr> cine imaging in the plane of the right ventricular outflow tract and axial reconstruction <b>(b)</b> from the <abbr title="three-dimensional">3D</abbr> <abbr title="steady-state free precession">SSFP</abbr> dataset demonstrate the baffle (<b>*</b>) along the posterior wall of the main pulmonary artery (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160124&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160124/asset/images/large/rg.2017160124.fig13b.jpeg" height="1701" width="1021" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. Takeuchi repair in a 36-year-old woman with <abbr title="anomalous origin of the left coronary artery from the pulmonary artery">ALCAPA</abbr>. MR imaging still frame <b>(a)</b> from two-dimensional (<abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr>) <abbr title="steady-state free precession">SSFP</abbr> cine imaging in the plane of the right ventricular outflow tract and axial reconstruction <b>(b)</b> from the <abbr title="three-dimensional">3D</abbr> <abbr title="steady-state free precession">SSFP</abbr> dataset demonstrate the baffle (<b>*</b>) along the posterior wall of the main pulmonary artery (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160124&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160124/asset/images/large/rg.2017160124.fig14.jpeg" height="1863" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14</span>. Diagram depicts ligation (long arrow) of the anomalous coronary artery at its pulmonary origin and placement of a bypass graft (short arrow) from the ascending aorta to the anomalous coronary artery. Note the regression of the intercoronary collaterals (dashed lines) and the normal-caliber coronary arteries after the surgery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160124&amp;id=fig14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160124/asset/images/large/rg.2017160124.fig15.jpeg" height="1999" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span>. Stenosis of the coronary button transfer site in a 24-year-old man with <abbr title="anomalous origin of the left coronary artery from the pulmonary artery">ALCAPA</abbr>. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows severe stenosis (arrow) at the proximal anastomosis, which was bypassed using a <abbr title="right internal mammary artery">RIMA</abbr> graft (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160124&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160124/asset/images/large/rg.2017160124.fig16a.jpeg" height="1628" width="1028" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span>. Supravalvular pulmonic stenosis after Takeuchi repair in a 19-year-old woman with <abbr title="anomalous origin of the left coronary artery from the pulmonary artery">ALCAPA</abbr>. MR imaging still frames from <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> <abbr title="steady-state free precession">SSFP</abbr> imaging in the plane of the right ventricular outflow tract in diastole <b>(a)</b> and systole <b>(b)</b> show a patent baffle (long arrow) posterior to the pulmonary artery. There is supravalvular stenosis of the pulmonary artery (short arrow) with a dephasing jet in systole (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160124&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160124/asset/images/large/rg.2017160124.fig16b.jpeg" height="1628" width="1022" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span>. Supravalvular pulmonic stenosis after Takeuchi repair in a 19-year-old woman with <abbr title="anomalous origin of the left coronary artery from the pulmonary artery">ALCAPA</abbr>. MR imaging still frames from <abbr title="two-dimensional">2D</abbr> <abbr title="steady-state free precession">SSFP</abbr> imaging in the plane of the right ventricular outflow tract in diastole <b>(a)</b> and systole <b>(b)</b> show a patent baffle (long arrow) posterior to the pulmonary artery. There is supravalvular stenosis of the pulmonary artery (short arrow) with a dephasing jet in systole (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160124&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160124/asset/images/large/rg.2017160124.fig17.jpeg" height="2031" width="1200" aria-labelledby="fig17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17</span>. Irregular dilatation of a graft in a 42-year-old man with <abbr title="anomalous origin of the left coronary artery from the pulmonary artery">ALCAPA</abbr>.Repair was by ligation of the anomalous origin and saphenous vein graft (arrow) from the ascending aorta to the left main coronary artery. Volume-rendered contrast-enhanced CT image reveals irregular dilatation of the venous graft.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160124&amp;id=fig17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160124/asset/images/large/rg.2017160124.fig18a.jpeg" height="1236" width="1089" aria-labelledby="fig18a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span>. <abbr title="coronary arterial fistula">CAF</abbr> in an asymptomatic 18-year-old man with a continuous murmur at presentation. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial ECG-gated cardiac CT angiographic images demonstrate a left circumflex <abbr title="coronary arterial fistula">CAF</abbr> with the right atrium. Note a markedly dilated left main coronary artery (arrow in <b>a</b>) and left circumflex coronary artery <b>(b)</b> draining into the right atrium with a contrast jet (arrow in <b>b</b>) at the site of communication with the right atrium. This is a large proximal Sakakibara type A single coronary cameral fistula. The right ventricle (<b>*</b>) is dilated. <b>(c)</b> Catheter angiography was performed and the fistula was corrected with a 22-mm Amplatzer vascular plug (ends indicated by arrows) with mild residual flow across the device (due to incomplete occlusion). <b>(d)</b> Two days later, a catheter angiogram shows migration of the Amplatzer device (arrow) to the right of the spine, with persistent residual flow across the fistula. <b>(e)</b> This was confirmed on a coronal oblique contrast-enhanced CT image, which shows device (<b>*</b>) migration toward the right atrium and a dilated left circumflex artery (arrow). At follow-up, the patient had increased flow within the fistula and required coil embolization (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160124&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160124/asset/images/large/rg.2017160124.fig18b.jpeg" height="1236" width="1238" aria-labelledby="fig18b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span>. <abbr title="coronary arterial fistula">CAF</abbr> in an asymptomatic 18-year-old man with a continuous murmur at presentation. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial ECG-gated cardiac CT angiographic images demonstrate a left circumflex <abbr title="coronary arterial fistula">CAF</abbr> with the right atrium. Note a markedly dilated left main coronary artery (arrow in <b>a</b>) and left circumflex coronary artery <b>(b)</b> draining into the right atrium with a contrast jet (arrow in <b>b</b>) at the site of communication with the right atrium. This is a large proximal Sakakibara type A single coronary cameral fistula. The right ventricle (<b>*</b>) is dilated. <b>(c)</b> Catheter angiography was performed and the fistula was corrected with a 22-mm Amplatzer vascular plug (ends indicated by arrows) with mild residual flow across the device (due to incomplete occlusion). <b>(d)</b> Two days later, a catheter angiogram shows migration of the Amplatzer device (arrow) to the right of the spine, with persistent residual flow across the fistula. <b>(e)</b> This was confirmed on a coronal oblique contrast-enhanced CT image, which shows device (<b>*</b>) migration toward the right atrium and a dilated left circumflex artery (arrow). At follow-up, the patient had increased flow within the fistula and required coil embolization (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160124&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160124/asset/images/large/rg.2017160124.fig18c.jpeg" height="1236" width="1373" aria-labelledby="fig18c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18c</span>. <abbr title="coronary arterial fistula">CAF</abbr> in an asymptomatic 18-year-old man with a continuous murmur at presentation. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial ECG-gated cardiac CT angiographic images demonstrate a left circumflex <abbr title="coronary arterial fistula">CAF</abbr> with the right atrium. Note a markedly dilated left main coronary artery (arrow in <b>a</b>) and left circumflex coronary artery <b>(b)</b> draining into the right atrium with a contrast jet (arrow in <b>b</b>) at the site of communication with the right atrium. This is a large proximal Sakakibara type A single coronary cameral fistula. The right ventricle (<b>*</b>) is dilated. <b>(c)</b> Catheter angiography was performed and the fistula was corrected with a 22-mm Amplatzer vascular plug (ends indicated by arrows) with mild residual flow across the device (due to incomplete occlusion). <b>(d)</b> Two days later, a catheter angiogram shows migration of the Amplatzer device (arrow) to the right of the spine, with persistent residual flow across the fistula. <b>(e)</b> This was confirmed on a coronal oblique contrast-enhanced CT image, which shows device (<b>*</b>) migration toward the right atrium and a dilated left circumflex artery (arrow). At follow-up, the patient had increased flow within the fistula and required coil embolization (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160124&amp;id=fig18c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160124/asset/images/large/rg.2017160124.fig18d.jpeg" height="953" width="1561" aria-labelledby="fig18d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18d</span>. <abbr title="coronary arterial fistula">CAF</abbr> in an asymptomatic 18-year-old man with a continuous murmur at presentation. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial ECG-gated cardiac CT angiographic images demonstrate a left circumflex <abbr title="coronary arterial fistula">CAF</abbr> with the right atrium. Note a markedly dilated left main coronary artery (arrow in <b>a</b>) and left circumflex coronary artery <b>(b)</b> draining into the right atrium with a contrast jet (arrow in <b>b</b>) at the site of communication with the right atrium. This is a large proximal Sakakibara type A single coronary cameral fistula. The right ventricle (<b>*</b>) is dilated. <b>(c)</b> Catheter angiography was performed and the fistula was corrected with a 22-mm Amplatzer vascular plug (ends indicated by arrows) with mild residual flow across the device (due to incomplete occlusion). <b>(d)</b> Two days later, a catheter angiogram shows migration of the Amplatzer device (arrow) to the right of the spine, with persistent residual flow across the fistula. <b>(e)</b> This was confirmed on a coronal oblique contrast-enhanced CT image, which shows device (<b>*</b>) migration toward the right atrium and a dilated left circumflex artery (arrow). At follow-up, the patient had increased flow within the fistula and required coil embolization (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160124&amp;id=fig18d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160124/asset/images/large/rg.2017160124.fig18e.jpeg" height="953" width="1789" aria-labelledby="fig18e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18e</span>. <abbr title="coronary arterial fistula">CAF</abbr> in an asymptomatic 18-year-old man with a continuous murmur at presentation. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial ECG-gated cardiac CT angiographic images demonstrate a left circumflex <abbr title="coronary arterial fistula">CAF</abbr> with the right atrium. Note a markedly dilated left main coronary artery (arrow in <b>a</b>) and left circumflex coronary artery <b>(b)</b> draining into the right atrium with a contrast jet (arrow in <b>b</b>) at the site of communication with the right atrium. This is a large proximal Sakakibara type A single coronary cameral fistula. The right ventricle (<b>*</b>) is dilated. <b>(c)</b> Catheter angiography was performed and the fistula was corrected with a 22-mm Amplatzer vascular plug (ends indicated by arrows) with mild residual flow across the device (due to incomplete occlusion). <b>(d)</b> Two days later, a catheter angiogram shows migration of the Amplatzer device (arrow) to the right of the spine, with persistent residual flow across the fistula. <b>(e)</b> This was confirmed on a coronal oblique contrast-enhanced CT image, which shows device (<b>*</b>) migration toward the right atrium and a dilated left circumflex artery (arrow). At follow-up, the patient had increased flow within the fistula and required coil embolization (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160124&amp;id=fig18e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160124/asset/images/large/rg.2017160124.fig19a.jpeg" height="1162" width="1578" aria-labelledby="fig19a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span>. Coronary cameral fistulain a 21-year-old man after bidirectional Glenn shunt and extracardiac Fontan for pulmonary atresia with intact ventricular septum, hypoplastic right ventricle, and hypoplastic tricuspid valve annulus. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial-contrast enhanced CT images demonstrate <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr> <b>(a)</b> with dilated origin (arrow) and <abbr title="left anterior descending coronary artery">LAD</abbr> <b>(b)</b> with dilatation (arrow). There is unopacified blood (<b>*</b>) in the extracardiac Fontan during the arterial phase. <b>(c)</b> The site of communication (arrow) of the <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr> fistula with the right ventricle is seen on a caudal axial CT image. <b>(d)</b> A <abbr title="three-dimensional">3D</abbr> volume-rendered image shows dilated <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr> (<b>*</b>) and <abbr title="left anterior descending coronary artery">LAD</abbr> (arrow). The communication of the <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr> fistula with the right ventricle is shown in blue and <abbr title="left anterior descending coronary artery">LAD</abbr> fistula with the right ventricle is shown in red.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160124&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160124/asset/images/large/rg.2017160124.fig19b.jpeg" height="1161" width="1372" aria-labelledby="fig19b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span>. Coronary cameral fistulain a 21-year-old man after bidirectional Glenn shunt and extracardiac Fontan for pulmonary atresia with intact ventricular septum, hypoplastic right ventricle, and hypoplastic tricuspid valve annulus. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial-contrast enhanced CT images demonstrate <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr> <b>(a)</b> with dilated origin (arrow) and <abbr title="left anterior descending coronary artery">LAD</abbr> <b>(b)</b> with dilatation (arrow). There is unopacified blood (<b>*</b>) in the extracardiac Fontan during the arterial phase. <b>(c)</b> The site of communication (arrow) of the <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr> fistula with the right ventricle is seen on a caudal axial CT image. <b>(d)</b> A <abbr title="three-dimensional">3D</abbr> volume-rendered image shows dilated <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr> (<b>*</b>) and <abbr title="left anterior descending coronary artery">LAD</abbr> (arrow). The communication of the <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr> fistula with the right ventricle is shown in blue and <abbr title="left anterior descending coronary artery">LAD</abbr> fistula with the right ventricle is shown in red.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160124&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160124/asset/images/large/rg.2017160124.fig19c.jpeg" height="1350" width="1546" aria-labelledby="fig19c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19c</span>. Coronary cameral fistulain a 21-year-old man after bidirectional Glenn shunt and extracardiac Fontan for pulmonary atresia with intact ventricular septum, hypoplastic right ventricle, and hypoplastic tricuspid valve annulus. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial-contrast enhanced CT images demonstrate <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr> <b>(a)</b> with dilated origin (arrow) and <abbr title="left anterior descending coronary artery">LAD</abbr> <b>(b)</b> with dilatation (arrow). There is unopacified blood (<b>*</b>) in the extracardiac Fontan during the arterial phase. <b>(c)</b> The site of communication (arrow) of the <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr> fistula with the right ventricle is seen on a caudal axial CT image. <b>(d)</b> A <abbr title="three-dimensional">3D</abbr> volume-rendered image shows dilated <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr> (<b>*</b>) and <abbr title="left anterior descending coronary artery">LAD</abbr> (arrow). The communication of the <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr> fistula with the right ventricle is shown in blue and <abbr title="left anterior descending coronary artery">LAD</abbr> fistula with the right ventricle is shown in red.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160124&amp;id=fig19c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160124/asset/images/large/rg.2017160124.fig19d.jpeg" height="1350" width="1104" aria-labelledby="fig19d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19d</span>. Coronary cameral fistulain a 21-year-old man after bidirectional Glenn shunt and extracardiac Fontan for pulmonary atresia with intact ventricular septum, hypoplastic right ventricle, and hypoplastic tricuspid valve annulus. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial-contrast enhanced CT images demonstrate <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr> <b>(a)</b> with dilated origin (arrow) and <abbr title="left anterior descending coronary artery">LAD</abbr> <b>(b)</b> with dilatation (arrow). There is unopacified blood (<b>*</b>) in the extracardiac Fontan during the arterial phase. <b>(c)</b> The site of communication (arrow) of the <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr> fistula with the right ventricle is seen on a caudal axial CT image. <b>(d)</b> A <abbr title="three-dimensional">3D</abbr> volume-rendered image shows dilated <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr> (<b>*</b>) and <abbr title="left anterior descending coronary artery">LAD</abbr> (arrow). The communication of the <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr> fistula with the right ventricle is shown in blue and <abbr title="left anterior descending coronary artery">LAD</abbr> fistula with the right ventricle is shown in red.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160124&amp;id=fig19d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160124/asset/images/large/rg.2017160124.fig20a.jpeg" height="1527" width="1399" aria-labelledby="fig20a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20a</span>. Repair of <abbr title="coronary arterial fistula">CAF</abbr> in a 45-year-old woman with atypical chest pain, shortness of breath at exertion, and continuous murmur, with an <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr>-to–coronary sinus fistula (Sakakibara type B). <b>(a)</b> Catheter angiogram shows platinum embolization coils (arrow), which were placed in the orifice of the fistula with the coronary sinus. <b>(b)</b> Posttreatment axial arterial phase CT image shows the coils (arrow), with the <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr> (<b>*</b>) demonstrating poor contrast opacification. <b>(c)</b> Axial 10-minute-delayed CT image shows a filling defect (arrow) in the <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr> due to thrombus after occlusion of the fistula. The patient had a small periprocedural infarct in the <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr> territory.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160124&amp;id=fig20a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160124/asset/images/large/rg.2017160124.fig20b.jpeg" height="1270" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig20b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20b</span>. Repair of <abbr title="coronary arterial fistula">CAF</abbr> in a 45-year-old woman with atypical chest pain, shortness of breath at exertion, and continuous murmur, with an <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr>-to–coronary sinus fistula (Sakakibara type B). <b>(a)</b> Catheter angiogram shows platinum embolization coils (arrow), which were placed in the orifice of the fistula with the coronary sinus. <b>(b)</b> Posttreatment axial arterial phase CT image shows the coils (arrow), with the <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr> (<b>*</b>) demonstrating poor contrast opacification. <b>(c)</b> Axial 10-minute-delayed CT image shows a filling defect (arrow) in the <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr> due to thrombus after occlusion of the fistula. The patient had a small periprocedural infarct in the <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr> territory.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160124&amp;id=fig20b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160124/asset/images/large/rg.2017160124.fig20c.jpeg" height="1528" width="1051" aria-labelledby="fig20c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20c</span>. Repair of <abbr title="coronary arterial fistula">CAF</abbr> in a 45-year-old woman with atypical chest pain, shortness of breath at exertion, and continuous murmur, with an <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr>-to–coronary sinus fistula (Sakakibara type B). <b>(a)</b> Catheter angiogram shows platinum embolization coils (arrow), which were placed in the orifice of the fistula with the coronary sinus. <b>(b)</b> Posttreatment axial arterial phase CT image shows the coils (arrow), with the <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr> (<b>*</b>) demonstrating poor contrast opacification. <b>(c)</b> Axial 10-minute-delayed CT image shows a filling defect (arrow) in the <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr> due to thrombus after occlusion of the fistula. The patient had a small periprocedural infarct in the <abbr title="right coronary artery">RCA</abbr> territory.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160124&amp;id=fig20c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" dat